  "eprint": {
    "title": "Database Reconstruction Attacks in Two Dimensions",
    "authors": [
      {
        "name": "Evangelia Anna Markatou",
        "email": "evangelia-anna_markatou@brown",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Roberto Tamassia",
        "email": "",
        "affiliation": ""
      }
    ],
    "abstract": "Access and search pattern leakage have been shown to be detrimental to the security of encrypted databases that allow for range queries, as shown by an extensive body of work on efficient attacks that reconstruct one-dimensional databases.\nWe are the first to go beyond one dimension, exploring the threat of access and search pattern leakage in two dimensions.\nFirst, we unveil  an intrinsic  limitation of reconstruction attacks by showing that there can be an exponential number of distinct databases that produce the same access and search pattern leakage. Next, we present attacks that reconstruct (1) the horizontal and vertical order of the points from the access pattern leakage, and (2) the coordinates of the points from the access and search pattern leakage.\nOur algorithms run in polynomial time  and return a linear-size encoding of all  databases consistent with the given leakage profile.",
    "keywords": [
      "Searchable Encryption",
      "Encrypted Databases",
      "Leakage-Abuse Attacks"
    ],
    "category": "Applications",
    "publication_info": "Preprint. MINOR revision.",
